blocks.caption:
If the factor has no effect, both variances estimate the same $\sigma^2$ and $F\approx1$. A real systematic effect inflates only the numerator, making $F>1$ — so the test is **one-tailed**: compare $F_{exp}$ only with the **upper** Fisher limit $F_U=$ F.INV.RT$(\alpha;
u_1;
u_2)$, with $
u_1=k-1$ (between) and $
u_2=k(n-1)$ (within). Equivalently the p-value is F.DIST.RT$(F_{exp};
u_1;
u_2)$.

practice.theory:
Single-factor ANOVA dof: between $k-1$, within $k(n-1)$, total $kn-1$; use $
u_1,
u_2$ in $F_U=\mathrm{F.INV.RT}(\alpha;
u_1;
u_2)$.

exam.tips:
The within-groups variance is the clean reference (denominator). The F-test is one-tailed — compare with $F_U=$ F.INV.RT$(\alpha;
u_1;
u_2)$ only. Keep $
u_1=k-1$ and $
u_2=k(n-1)$ straight; swapping them changes $F_U$.
